<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-148-068 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 781 680</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  May 27 1991 n643 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sony sends CD-ROM home. (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Doherty, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sony Corp is introducing Laser-Library, a CD-ROM reader retailingfor $699.andP;  Designed for use with a home or office PC, it alsoplays audio CDs.andP;  The reader comes with six CD-ROMs includingencyclopedias, language translators, atlases, dictionaries,business references and interactive educational and entertainmentsoftware.andP;  Sony is hoping that the new player with its $2,000worth of CDs included will stimulate the market for more titles.andO;It is planning on releasing dozens of CD-ROM titles in 1991 andsupplying them through a toll-free ordering number included withLaser-Library.andP;  Sony is offering CD publishers guaranteed sales'unprecedented in the industry.' To use the player an IBMcompatible PC with DOS 3.1 or higher and 512-Kbytes of RAM.andP;  Thisis Sony's first venture into PC peripherals, although it does havea track record in audio CD players.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Sony Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Sony Laser Library (CD-ROM drive) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     CD-ROMProduct IntroductionBundled SoftwareDisk Drives.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>